e:["$","div",null,{"className":"blog-post-view","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"blog-post-header","style":{"background":"#e0e7ff"},"children":["$","div",null,{"className":"blog-post-header-inner","children":[["$","$L17",null,{"href":"/blog","className":"back-btn","children":"← Back to Blog"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"blog-tag","style":{"marginBottom":"1rem","display":"inline-block"},"children":"Office Furniture"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"blog-post-title","children":"Standing Desk Review: Is It Worth the Switch?"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"blog-post-meta","children":[["$","span",null,{"children":"June 12, 2026"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"·"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"10 min read"}]]}]]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"blog-post-body","children":[["$","p","p-0",{"children":"I resisted standing desks for years. The price felt hard to justify, and I wasn't convinced the health benefits were as significant as the marketing suggested. Then my back started complaining after long writing sessions, and I decided it was time to actually test a few."}],"\n",["$","p","p-1",{"children":"Over 90 days I used five different standing desks — ranging from a $129 converter to a $650 full motorized setup. Here's the honest breakdown."}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-0",{"children":"The Desks I Tested"}],"\n",["$","table","table-0",{"children":[["$","thead","thead-0",{"children":["$","tr","tr-0",{"children":[["$","th","th-0",{"children":"Desk"}],["$","th","th-1",{"children":"Type"}],["$","th","th-2",{"children":"Price"}]]}]}],["$","tbody","tbody-0",{"children":[["$","tr","tr-0",{"children":[["$","td","td-0",{"children":"FLEXISPOT E7"}],["$","td","td-1",{"children":"Motorized, full"}],["$","td","td-2",{"children":"$$499"}]]}],["$","tr","tr-1",{"children":[["$","td","td-0",{"children":"Vari Electric 60x30"}],["$","td","td-1",{"children":"Motorized, full"}],["$","td","td-2",{"children":"$$645"}]]}],["$","tr","tr-2",{"children":[["$","td","td-0",{"children":"SHW 55\" Electric"}],["$","td","td-1",{"children":"Motorized, full"}],["$","td","td-2",{"children":"$$329"}]]}],["$","tr","tr-3",{"children":[["$","td","td-0",{"children":"FLEXISPOT M7"}],["$","td","td-1",{"children":"Converter"}],["$","td","td-2",{"children":"$$299"}]]}],["$","tr","tr-4",{"children":[["$","td","td-0",{"children":"Standing desk converter (35\")"}],["$","td","td-1",{"children":"Converter"}],["$","td","td-2",{"children":"$$129"}]]}]]}]]}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-1",{"children":"What Actually Matters"}],"\n",["$","p","p-2",{"children":"Before the individual reviews, here's what I learned matters most:"}],"\n",["$","p","p-3",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Stability at standing height."}]," A wobbly desk at standing height is useless. You'll feel it through your keyboard and mouse on every keystroke. This eliminated two of the five desks within the first week."]}],"\n",["$","p","p-4",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Motor speed and noise."}]," Nobody wants to wait 30 seconds for their desk to move, and nobody wants a noise complaint from the next room. The best motors in this test took 5–7 seconds to travel the full range."]}],"\n",["$","p","p-5",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Memory presets."}]," This sounds like a luxury until you realize you'll be switching positions 6–8 times a day. Without memory buttons, you'll stop switching and just leave it at one height."]}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-2",{"children":"The Winner: FLEXISPOT E7"}],"\n",["$","p","p-6",{"children":"For most home offices, the FLEXISPOT E7 offers the best combination of stability, motor quality, and price. It supports up to 355 lbs, moves quickly, and doesn't wobble at standing height even with a 34-inch monitor arm attached."}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-3",{"children":"Budget Pick: SHW 55\" Electric"}],"\n",["$","p","p-7",{"children":"If $499 isn't in the budget, the SHW offers a solid motorized experience at $329. It's slightly less stable than the FLEXISPOT and the motor is noisier, but it gets the job done. Good first standing desk."}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-4",{"children":"Converters: A Different Answer to a Different Question"}],"\n","$L18","\n","$L19","\n","$L1a","\n","$L1b"]}]]}]
18:["$","p","p-8",{"children":"Converters don't replace a desk — they sit on top of one. If your current desk is already the right height for sitting, a converter is a lower-commitment entry point. The FLEXISPOT M7 is the best I tested in this category. But if you have the budget and the space, a full motorized desk is the better long-term investment."}]
19:["$","h2","h2-5",{"children":"The Honest Health Verdict"}]
1a:["$","p","p-9",{"children":["Standing desks help with back discomfort — but only if you also move. Standing in the same position for four hours straight is nearly as bad as sitting. The real benefit comes from the ",["$","em","em-0",{"children":"switching"}],". Standing for 20–30 minutes, sitting for an hour, standing again. A good anti-fatigue mat makes a real difference too."]}]
1b:["$","p","p-10",{"children":"Worth the investment? For a home office setup you'll use long-term: yes."}]
